'''Emory McClintock''' (1840–1916), born '''John Emory McClintock''' was an [[United States|American]] [[actuary]], born in [[Carlisle, Pennsylvania|Carlisle]], [[Pennsylvania]].  He graduated from [[Columbia University]], where he was tutor in mathematics in 1859–1860.  From 1863 to 1866 he served as United States consular agent at [[Bradford]], [[England]].  He served as president of the [[American Mathematical Society]] in 1890–1894 and of the [[Society of Actuaries|Actuarial Society of America]] in 1895–1897.

==Early life and career==
He was born to [[John McClintock (theologian)|John]] and Caroline Augusta Wakeman McClintock.  His father was a minister of the [[Methodist Episcopal Church]], who was also a Professor of  mathematics, and ancient languages at [[Dickinson College]] in [[Carlisle, Pennsylvania|Carlisle]].<ref>[http://chronicles.dickinson.edu/encyclo/m/ed_McClintockJE.html  J(ohn) Emory McClintock], Dickinson College</ref>  His father was also involved in an 1847 a riot over slavery, as he tried to prevent slavechasers from taking African-American citizens of Pennsylvania into slavery.<ref>[http://chronicles.dickinson.edu/encyclo/m/ed_mcClintockJ.htm John McClintock], Dickinson College</ref>
He was actuary of the [[Asbury Life Insurance Company]], [[New York City|New York]] (1867–1871), of the [[Northwestern Mutual Life Insurance Company]], [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin|Milwaukee]], [[Wisconsin]], (1871–1889), and of the [[Metropolitan Life Insurance Company|Mutual Life Insurance Company]], New York (1889–1911).  Of the Mutual he was vice president in 1905–1911, trustee after 1905, and consulting actuary after 1911.

